WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:01.420 --> 00:00:03.270
NATHAN RUNKLE: So my name
is Nathan Runkle.

00:00:03.270 --> 00:00:06.020
I'm the founder and executive
director of Mercy For Animals.

00:00:06.020 --> 00:00:09.630
And we are a national, nonprofit
animal protection

00:00:09.630 --> 00:00:10.390
organization.

00:00:10.390 --> 00:00:13.980
And our mission is to prevent
cruelty to farmed animals, and

00:00:13.980 --> 00:00:17.330
promote compassionate food
choices and policies.

00:00:17.330 --> 00:00:20.920
So I want to talk for a few
minutes about how I got

00:00:20.920 --> 00:00:24.910
involved in animal protection
issues.

00:00:24.910 --> 00:00:29.890
This is me in St. Paris, Ohio,
a town of about 2,000 people.

00:00:29.890 --> 00:00:34.300
I was born on a farm, come
from a long heritage of

00:00:34.300 --> 00:00:36.800
farmers, four generations.

00:00:36.800 --> 00:00:39.500
In this photo, my father is, I
think, breaking all sorts of

00:00:39.500 --> 00:00:42.000
state and federal laws,
potentially--

00:00:42.000 --> 00:00:44.910
child endangerment.

00:00:44.910 --> 00:00:47.670
But growing up in this
environment, I always had a

00:00:47.670 --> 00:00:50.780
natural affinity and connection
for animals.

00:00:50.780 --> 00:00:54.790
I spent much of my childhood
exploring the nearby creeks

00:00:54.790 --> 00:00:59.170
and streams and looking
at wildlife.

00:00:59.170 --> 00:01:02.670
And it was our dogs and cats
that were the first to teach

00:01:02.670 --> 00:01:07.340
me that other creatures share
our needs and our desires,

00:01:07.340 --> 00:01:10.170
that they have curiosities,
senses of humor.

00:01:10.170 --> 00:01:13.600
And it wasn't something that
I had to study in school.

00:01:13.600 --> 00:01:18.650
But from a young age, I
witnessed the contradictory

00:01:18.650 --> 00:01:21.570
view that we hold for animals.

00:01:21.570 --> 00:01:25.570
I saw that our family cared very
much about the dogs and

00:01:25.570 --> 00:01:29.000
cats that we had, but we did
not have the same level of

00:01:29.000 --> 00:01:32.600
compassion or empathy or respect
for other animals.

00:01:32.600 --> 00:01:34.940
So both of my uncles
were hunters and

00:01:34.940 --> 00:01:36.440
trappers and fishermen.

00:01:36.440 --> 00:01:39.050
So from a young age, I witnessed
animals being

00:01:39.050 --> 00:01:41.880
skinned while they were still
alive, having their heads

00:01:41.880 --> 00:01:43.850
ripped off while they
were still alive.

00:01:43.850 --> 00:01:47.550
And most people in my social
circle did not afford those

00:01:47.550 --> 00:01:49.230
animals much consideration.

00:01:49.230 --> 00:01:51.680
And that always felt
wrong to me.

00:01:51.680 --> 00:01:55.030
I thought that we could and
should do much better.

00:01:55.030 --> 00:01:57.940
There was a local animal
abuse case when I

00:01:57.940 --> 00:02:00.020
was 15, so in 1999.

00:02:00.020 --> 00:02:03.540
That is what ultimately led to
me founding Mercy For Animals.

00:02:03.540 --> 00:02:06.930
And it was at a local high
school, and there was a

00:02:06.930 --> 00:02:10.680
teacher there who had an
agricultural class.

00:02:10.680 --> 00:02:13.900
And this teacher also
ran a pig farm.

00:02:13.900 --> 00:02:17.040
Now, one day he brought to
school a bucket of day-old

00:02:17.040 --> 00:02:19.710
piglets to be used in a
dissection project.

00:02:19.710 --> 00:02:21.910
Now, these were piglets that
he had tried to kill that

00:02:21.910 --> 00:02:23.730
morning on his farm.

00:02:23.730 --> 00:02:25.740
But when he arrived to the
school, one of the piglets was

00:02:25.740 --> 00:02:27.340
still alive.

00:02:27.340 --> 00:02:30.480
A student in the class who also
did part-time work on the

00:02:30.480 --> 00:02:34.210
teacher's pig farm took the
piglet by her hind legs and

00:02:34.210 --> 00:02:37.240
slammed her head-first into
the ground to try

00:02:37.240 --> 00:02:38.800
to kill this piglet.

00:02:38.800 --> 00:02:40.590
Now, the piglet didn't die.

00:02:40.590 --> 00:02:41.880
Her skull was broken.

00:02:41.880 --> 00:02:42.990
She was bleeding out
of her mouth.

00:02:42.990 --> 00:02:44.680
She's in horrible distress.

00:02:44.680 --> 00:02:48.040
A few of the students who were
appalled by this act of abuse

00:02:48.040 --> 00:02:52.110
took the dying piglet, left the
classroom, and took her to

00:02:52.110 --> 00:02:54.760
a teacher who was known as
being a vegetarian and

00:02:54.760 --> 00:02:56.740
sympathetic to animal cruelty.

00:02:56.740 --> 00:02:59.360
That teacher left the school,
went to a local vet office,

00:02:59.360 --> 00:03:01.800
and had the piglet euthanized.

00:03:01.800 --> 00:03:04.450
Now, following that case,
there were two counts of

00:03:04.450 --> 00:03:06.710
animal cruelty that were filed,
one against the student

00:03:06.710 --> 00:03:08.150
and one against the teacher.

00:03:08.150 --> 00:03:11.260
Now, the case generated a lot
of media attention and

00:03:11.260 --> 00:03:14.920
controversy in this small
farm community.

00:03:14.920 --> 00:03:17.810
And the pig farming community
rallied behind

00:03:17.810 --> 00:03:18.770
the student and teacher.

00:03:18.770 --> 00:03:21.390
And they said, we don't want
animal advocates coming into

00:03:21.390 --> 00:03:24.630
our town, telling us
how to do our jobs.

00:03:24.630 --> 00:03:27.250
The very first day of the trial,
the cruelty charges

00:03:27.250 --> 00:03:31.010
were dismissed, because it's
considered standard

00:03:31.010 --> 00:03:34.170
agricultural practice to kill
piglets by slamming them

00:03:34.170 --> 00:03:35.870
head-first into the ground.

00:03:35.870 --> 00:03:39.240
And in Ohio, like at least 30
other states in this country,

00:03:39.240 --> 00:03:41.870
if something is considered
standard agricultural

00:03:41.870 --> 00:03:45.090
practice, no matter how cruel
it is, it's exempt from

00:03:45.090 --> 00:03:46.590
cruelty prosecution.

00:03:46.590 --> 00:03:50.050
So that case illustrated to me
that there needed to be a

00:03:50.050 --> 00:03:53.580
voice for farm animals in
this community in Ohio.

00:03:53.580 --> 00:03:56.520
So since then, Mercy For Animals
has grown to having

00:03:56.520 --> 00:03:59.240
over 100,000 members
and supporters.

00:03:59.240 --> 00:04:01.230
We have five offices
across the country.

00:04:01.230 --> 00:04:04.240
And we work to give a voice to
farmed animals in four main

00:04:04.240 --> 00:04:07.030
areas-- through public education
campaigns, through

00:04:07.030 --> 00:04:09.970
undercover cruelty
investigations, through

00:04:09.970 --> 00:04:13.690
corporate outreach, and legal
advocacy efforts.

00:04:13.690 --> 00:04:15.540
All right, so there
you have it.

00:04:15.540 --> 00:04:18.740
Now, I want to start out by
talking a bit about animals

00:04:18.740 --> 00:04:20.480
and our relationship
to animals and

00:04:20.480 --> 00:04:22.480
why we should care.

00:04:22.480 --> 00:04:24.385
Now, Dr. Jane Goodall once said,
"we have to understand

00:04:24.385 --> 00:04:29.030
we are not the only beings on
this planet with personalities

00:04:29.030 --> 00:04:33.500
and minds." Now as I'm sure
many of you are aware, Dr.

00:04:33.500 --> 00:04:37.510
Goodall spent about 45 years
in Africa living with and

00:04:37.510 --> 00:04:39.380
studying chimpanzees.

00:04:39.380 --> 00:04:42.620
She was one of the first
researchers to give her

00:04:42.620 --> 00:04:45.760
subjects names as opposed
to numbers.

00:04:45.760 --> 00:04:48.400
And she started to observe them
and find out that many of

00:04:48.400 --> 00:04:52.380
the traits that we once held so
closely as being unique to

00:04:52.380 --> 00:04:55.640
people are in fact not unique
and are very widespread in the

00:04:55.640 --> 00:04:57.070
animal community--

00:04:57.070 --> 00:05:00.700
things like culture and empathy
and compassion, things

00:05:00.700 --> 00:05:04.390
like not only using tools,
but creating tools.

00:05:04.390 --> 00:05:10.310
So Dr. Goodall started to tear
down these various boundaries.

00:05:10.310 --> 00:05:13.000
And I think looking at
this image really

00:05:13.000 --> 00:05:14.710
illustrates it so perfectly.

00:05:14.710 --> 00:05:17.500
We know that other animals feel
cold, the cold of this

00:05:17.500 --> 00:05:22.560
metal, the heat of the sun, that
they form relationships

00:05:22.560 --> 00:05:26.640
and bonds, and that they, too,
deserve our consideration.

00:05:26.640 --> 00:05:30.400
Now, anyone who has shared their
homes with dogs or cats

00:05:30.400 --> 00:05:31.220
knows this.

00:05:31.220 --> 00:05:34.420
We know how excited they are
when we come home, how eager

00:05:34.420 --> 00:05:37.990
they are for their walks,
how playful they are.

00:05:37.990 --> 00:05:40.080
And this is, again, not
something that we had to study

00:05:40.080 --> 00:05:42.700
animal behavior to know.

00:05:42.700 --> 00:05:45.230
And the scientific community is
finally starting to catch

00:05:45.230 --> 00:05:48.240
up to what so many of us
have known all along.

00:05:48.240 --> 00:05:53.410
Just this year, the University
of Cambridge published the

00:05:53.410 --> 00:05:55.310
Cambridge Declaration
of Consciousness.

00:05:55.310 --> 00:05:57.520
And essentially, this is
the first time that an

00:05:57.520 --> 00:06:00.610
international group of prominent
scientists supported

00:06:00.610 --> 00:06:03.370
the idea that animals are
conscious and aware to the

00:06:03.370 --> 00:06:05.590
same degree that humans are.

00:06:05.590 --> 00:06:08.330
Now, this was really
earth-shattering for this to

00:06:08.330 --> 00:06:11.590
come out, because they found
that not only do mammals have

00:06:11.590 --> 00:06:14.720
consciousness and dogs and cats,
but birds have the same

00:06:14.720 --> 00:06:17.785
level of consciousness, and not
only birds, but fish, and

00:06:17.785 --> 00:06:19.570
not only fish, but octopus.

00:06:19.570 --> 00:06:23.440
So this whole notion, I think,
should give all of us pause to

00:06:23.440 --> 00:06:26.000
really think about our treatment
of animals and our

00:06:26.000 --> 00:06:30.230
obligation to them, and how we
can include them in our circle

00:06:30.230 --> 00:06:32.480
of consideration and ethics.

00:06:32.480 --> 00:06:35.330
So what we do at Mercy For
Animals is help people step

00:06:35.330 --> 00:06:39.380
back and think about farm
animals as individuals with

00:06:39.380 --> 00:06:44.600
needs, and how we can respect
them and do due diligence in

00:06:44.600 --> 00:06:46.410
protecting their interests.

00:06:46.410 --> 00:06:47.740
So I want to talk a little
bit about who

00:06:47.740 --> 00:06:49.620
farmed animals are first.

00:06:49.620 --> 00:06:53.830
This is an image of the
wild ancestors of

00:06:53.830 --> 00:06:55.040
the modern-day chicken.

00:06:55.040 --> 00:06:56.560
Now, most people just think
of chickens and

00:06:56.560 --> 00:06:57.190
they think of barnyards.

00:06:57.190 --> 00:07:00.930
And Of course, these birds once
lived wild in the jungles

00:07:00.930 --> 00:07:02.360
of Southeast Asia.

00:07:02.360 --> 00:07:04.190
And they lived in a world
that was very rich

00:07:04.190 --> 00:07:05.840
with sound and color.

00:07:05.840 --> 00:07:10.110
And they lived in social groups
of about a dozen birds.

00:07:10.110 --> 00:07:12.860
And they were very active.

00:07:12.860 --> 00:07:15.910
Now, we manipulated these
animals to becoming almost

00:07:15.910 --> 00:07:18.560
genetic Frankensteins of
what they once were.

00:07:18.560 --> 00:07:20.750
And I'll talk about that
a little bit later.

00:07:20.750 --> 00:07:24.420
But we see that, even through
hundreds or thousands of years

00:07:24.420 --> 00:07:27.690
of domestication, these animals
still have the same

00:07:27.690 --> 00:07:29.700
behaviors, the same desires.

00:07:29.700 --> 00:07:33.070
These are egg-laying hens that
live their entire lives in

00:07:33.070 --> 00:07:34.350
tiny cages.

00:07:34.350 --> 00:07:36.760
And this is a photograph of them
about a month after they

00:07:36.760 --> 00:07:37.820
were rescued.

00:07:37.820 --> 00:07:41.110
And we see that these birds
still want to perch, roost,

00:07:41.110 --> 00:07:41.960
dust-bathe.

00:07:41.960 --> 00:07:44.600
They spend the night in trees.

00:07:44.600 --> 00:07:47.690
Now, the more that we know about
birds, the more respect

00:07:47.690 --> 00:07:48.690
we should have for them.

00:07:48.690 --> 00:07:51.760
We all know the term "the
watchful mother hen," and this

00:07:51.760 --> 00:07:54.700
is a term that these birds
really have earned.

00:07:54.700 --> 00:07:57.470
They will give their lives
to protect their young.

00:07:57.470 --> 00:07:59.960
They have a very close bond
with their young.

00:07:59.960 --> 00:08:02.090
They actually start to chirp
and communicate with them

00:08:02.090 --> 00:08:04.780
while they're still in the
eggs in the last few days

00:08:04.780 --> 00:08:05.960
before hatching.

00:08:05.960 --> 00:08:09.880
We know that birds can recognize
100 other birds

00:08:09.880 --> 00:08:12.780
based on their distinct
facial features.

00:08:12.780 --> 00:08:15.070
I think if most of us saw a
group of 100 chickens, we'd

00:08:15.070 --> 00:08:17.280
think that they all looked
pretty similar.

00:08:17.280 --> 00:08:20.190
But to them, they look as unique
and different as each

00:08:20.190 --> 00:08:22.940
of us do in this room to us.

00:08:22.940 --> 00:08:24.970
We know that they have
a language that

00:08:24.970 --> 00:08:26.210
is unique to them.

00:08:26.210 --> 00:08:29.120
We know at least 30 different
calls that they have that are

00:08:29.120 --> 00:08:33.080
unique for overhead predators
versus ground predators.

00:08:33.080 --> 00:08:36.280
They have a more intimate tone
and inflection that they use

00:08:36.280 --> 00:08:39.039
with birds that they consider
to be their friends.

00:08:39.039 --> 00:08:41.409
We know that chickens understand
that recently

00:08:41.409 --> 00:08:43.950
hidden objects still exist.

00:08:43.950 --> 00:08:46.860
They're not rocket science, but
this is beyond the ability

00:08:46.860 --> 00:08:50.030
of small human children.

00:08:50.030 --> 00:08:54.070
That has led Dr. Bernard Rollin
to state, "contrary to

00:08:54.070 --> 00:08:56.750
what one may hear from the
industry, chickens are complex

00:08:56.750 --> 00:09:00.510
behaviorally, do quite well in
learning, show a rich social

00:09:00.510 --> 00:09:03.600
organization, and have a diverse
repertoire of calls.

00:09:03.600 --> 00:09:06.330
Anyone who has kept barnyard
chickens recognizes their

00:09:06.330 --> 00:09:11.330
distinct differences in
personality." And of course,

00:09:11.330 --> 00:09:13.840
anyone who has spent any time
with chickens knows that there

00:09:13.840 --> 00:09:18.340
are some who like the attention
of people, who will

00:09:18.340 --> 00:09:20.700
follow you around and peck at
your toes, wanting treats, and

00:09:20.700 --> 00:09:23.100
others who would prefer
to be on their own.

00:09:23.100 --> 00:09:25.600
Now, the scientific community
is starting to catch up to

00:09:25.600 --> 00:09:26.460
this notion.

00:09:26.460 --> 00:09:29.270
This is an illustration that
appeared in "The Washington

00:09:29.270 --> 00:09:33.100
Post" in 2005, where the
scientific community called

00:09:33.100 --> 00:09:37.130
for a remapping of the bird
brain, saying that about 90%

00:09:37.130 --> 00:09:40.120
of the over-2,000 terms that
we use in referring to the

00:09:40.120 --> 00:09:42.270
structure of a bird
brain is outdated.

00:09:42.270 --> 00:09:45.140
It needs to be reevaluated.

00:09:45.140 --> 00:09:47.030
So what we see on the right-hand
side of this

00:09:47.030 --> 00:09:50.450
illustration is the traditional

00:09:50.450 --> 00:09:51.520
view of a bird's brain.

00:09:51.520 --> 00:09:54.630
And we see that most of it we
thought was just used for

00:09:54.630 --> 00:09:57.570
instinctive behaviors, that
birds were going around and

00:09:57.570 --> 00:10:00.690
just acting by instincts, with a
very small amount being used

00:10:00.690 --> 00:10:03.070
for cognitive behavior
or learning.

00:10:03.070 --> 00:10:05.310
But our new view, which we see
in the middle here, is that

00:10:05.310 --> 00:10:09.960
over 75% of the bird's brain is
used for complex cognitive

00:10:09.960 --> 00:10:11.210
behavior or learning.

00:10:15.130 --> 00:10:16.600
Now, pigs are also

00:10:16.600 --> 00:10:18.740
intelligent, sensitive creatures.

00:10:18.740 --> 00:10:21.170
Some people say that they're
the fourth-most intelligent

00:10:21.170 --> 00:10:23.700
creatures on the face
of the planet.

00:10:23.700 --> 00:10:26.890
We know that these animals have
strong bonds that they

00:10:26.890 --> 00:10:28.840
also form with their young.

00:10:28.840 --> 00:10:30.490
We know that they have
a unique language.

00:10:30.490 --> 00:10:33.020
We know of at least 20 different
grunts or oinks that

00:10:33.020 --> 00:10:35.600
they make that mean very
distinct things.

00:10:35.600 --> 00:10:37.480
And we know that they have
long-term memories.

00:10:37.480 --> 00:10:39.590
There was a study done at
Penn State University.

00:10:39.590 --> 00:10:41.870
They took a group of pigs
and they presented

00:10:41.870 --> 00:10:43.660
them with three objects.

00:10:43.660 --> 00:10:47.680
One was a dumbbell, one was a
Frisbee, and one was a ball.

00:10:47.680 --> 00:10:50.920
And they taught the pigs to pick
up the Frisbee, to sit

00:10:50.920 --> 00:10:53.690
next to the dumbbell, and
to jump over the ball.

00:10:53.690 --> 00:10:57.020
And they took those pigs away
for three years, without ever

00:10:57.020 --> 00:10:57.880
seeing those objects.

00:10:57.880 --> 00:11:00.080
Three years later, they brought
them back, presented

00:11:00.080 --> 00:11:03.030
them with the objects, and 100%
of the pigs, without any

00:11:03.030 --> 00:11:05.950
retraining or prompting,
remembered those behaviors

00:11:05.950 --> 00:11:10.480
that they were taught
three years before.

00:11:10.480 --> 00:11:12.820
Now, Dr. Donald Broom said,
"pigs have the cognitive

00:11:12.820 --> 00:11:14.500
ability to be sophisticated.

00:11:14.500 --> 00:11:17.120
Even more so than dogs and
certainly three-year-olds."

00:11:17.120 --> 00:11:19.070
He's talking about
three-year-old humans.

00:11:19.070 --> 00:11:22.420
Anyone who has children or
nieces or nephews knows just

00:11:22.420 --> 00:11:24.520
how intelligent three-year-olds
are, how they

00:11:24.520 --> 00:11:26.790
have a sense of humor
and curiosity.

00:11:26.790 --> 00:11:30.210
To think that that same level of
thinking is going on in the

00:11:30.210 --> 00:11:32.390
mind of a pig should give
us all pause to

00:11:32.390 --> 00:11:34.100
how we treat them.

00:11:34.100 --> 00:11:38.150
Now, researchers have taught
pigs how to play video games

00:11:38.150 --> 00:11:40.810
using remote-controlled
joysticks, showing that they

00:11:40.810 --> 00:11:42.550
understand cause and effect.

00:11:42.550 --> 00:11:45.750
Now, I have mixed feelings about
bringing an entire other

00:11:45.750 --> 00:11:48.710
species into the video
game revolution.

00:11:48.710 --> 00:11:51.110
I think it's causing problems
for our own species.

00:11:51.110 --> 00:11:54.380
But nevertheless, there it is.

00:11:54.380 --> 00:11:56.400
And then, of course, we have
cows, I think some of the most

00:11:56.400 --> 00:12:00.020
benevolent, peaceful creatures
on the planet.

00:12:00.020 --> 00:12:02.380
These are animals that,
again, form strong

00:12:02.380 --> 00:12:03.710
bonds with their young.

00:12:03.710 --> 00:12:06.220
We hear story after story of
mother cows who have been

00:12:06.220 --> 00:12:08.840
separated from their young,
not only bellowing out in

00:12:08.840 --> 00:12:12.290
distress for days on end, but
jumping over fences and

00:12:12.290 --> 00:12:16.590
traveling miles on end to be
relocated with their young.

00:12:16.590 --> 00:12:19.050
We know that cows have best
friends that they spend most

00:12:19.050 --> 00:12:21.790
of their time with, and that
they show excitement when they

00:12:21.790 --> 00:12:24.710
solve problems.

00:12:24.710 --> 00:12:27.740
And finally, I want to talk for
just a second about fish.

00:12:27.740 --> 00:12:30.820
Now, most people don't give
much thought to fish.

00:12:30.820 --> 00:12:34.160
And it's easy to really
disregard them, because they

00:12:34.160 --> 00:12:36.140
inhabit a world that
is so different

00:12:36.140 --> 00:12:37.900
from us, under water.

00:12:37.900 --> 00:12:40.540
They don't have the same ability
to express their

00:12:40.540 --> 00:12:42.260
feelings through facial
features.

00:12:42.260 --> 00:12:43.640
They can't scream.

00:12:43.640 --> 00:12:45.350
But fish are not swimming
vegetables.

00:12:45.350 --> 00:12:49.320
And we know that these animals
suffer pain and fear and

00:12:49.320 --> 00:12:52.090
distress in much the same
way that we do.

00:12:52.090 --> 00:12:54.950
They did a study where they took
fish and they injected

00:12:54.950 --> 00:12:57.060
bee venom under their scales.

00:12:57.060 --> 00:13:00.150
And what they found is that
the fish's heart rate

00:13:00.150 --> 00:13:03.290
elevated, that they started
swimming frantically back and

00:13:03.290 --> 00:13:06.750
forth in the enclosure, and
rubbing that area of their

00:13:06.750 --> 00:13:08.940
body against the enclosure.

00:13:08.940 --> 00:13:12.890
Their brains also release
natural painkillers.

00:13:12.890 --> 00:13:17.640
And they release oxytocin, our
natural feel-good drug.

00:13:17.640 --> 00:13:22.660
This is an illustration of the
structure of a fish brain

00:13:22.660 --> 00:13:23.690
versus a human brain.

00:13:23.690 --> 00:13:26.460
What we see is that, though
they may be structured

00:13:26.460 --> 00:13:30.230
differently, they still have
the same functions.

00:13:30.230 --> 00:13:32.420
So here we see that, on the
surface of the fish's

00:13:32.420 --> 00:13:33.940
[INAUDIBLE] brain, there are
structures that serve

00:13:33.940 --> 00:13:36.820
functions similar to the limbic
system of mammals.

00:13:36.820 --> 00:13:39.510
In mammals, these cerebellar
receptors are responsible,

00:13:39.510 --> 00:13:41.940
among other things, for the
emotional evaluation of

00:13:41.940 --> 00:13:45.170
information, and they play a
role in creating memories and

00:13:45.170 --> 00:13:46.710
the learning processes.

00:13:46.710 --> 00:13:49.380
And we know, too, that fish can
use tools, that some of

00:13:49.380 --> 00:13:53.365
them form life-long monogamous
relationships with other fish.

00:13:56.300 --> 00:13:58.830
And I say all this because
I think we've become so

00:13:58.830 --> 00:14:00.360
disconnected from
these animals.

00:14:00.360 --> 00:14:03.360
Few of us will ever spend much
time with a cow or a pig or a

00:14:03.360 --> 00:14:06.180
chicken, so it's good
to know this.

00:14:06.180 --> 00:14:09.360
But I really don't think it
matters all that much if these

00:14:09.360 --> 00:14:13.990
animals can solve mathematical
equations, because these are

00:14:13.990 --> 00:14:17.990
arbitrary tests that we've
created for other animals

00:14:17.990 --> 00:14:21.450
based on our own intelligence.

00:14:21.450 --> 00:14:23.730
Jeremy Bentham said, "the
question is not can they

00:14:23.730 --> 00:14:27.460
reason nor can they talk, but
can they suffer?" And I think

00:14:27.460 --> 00:14:30.020
that we are at a time where
there's really no legitimate

00:14:30.020 --> 00:14:32.360
debate now whether animals
can suffer.

00:14:32.360 --> 00:14:33.670
They have brains,
central nervous

00:14:33.670 --> 00:14:35.130
systems, nerve endings.

00:14:35.130 --> 00:14:38.560
Pain to them is used in the same
way as it is for us, as a

00:14:38.560 --> 00:14:41.960
way to move away from negative
stimuli to protect them.

00:14:41.960 --> 00:14:45.550
So I think the test that we have
as ethical, conscious,

00:14:45.550 --> 00:14:49.150
moral creatures is, how can we
live on this planet and do the

00:14:49.150 --> 00:14:51.570
most good and the least harm?

00:14:51.570 --> 00:14:56.370
And knowing that farm animals
suffer pain, how can we in

00:14:56.370 --> 00:14:59.130
good conscience ignore
their plight?

00:14:59.130 --> 00:15:00.940
So what is the plight
for these animals?

00:15:00.940 --> 00:15:06.150
Well, about 60, 70, 80 years
ago, most farm animals lived

00:15:06.150 --> 00:15:10.330
relatively decent lives, outside
in small flocks.

00:15:10.330 --> 00:15:13.570
And this is an illustration
showing that.

00:15:13.570 --> 00:15:16.670
Many of them were even
slaughtered on the farm.

00:15:16.670 --> 00:15:19.070
But unfortunately,
much has changed.

00:15:19.070 --> 00:15:22.640
In fact, so few people are
involved in agriculture now,

00:15:22.640 --> 00:15:24.910
less than 2%, that they're
removing it from the Census

00:15:24.910 --> 00:15:27.840
Bureau occupational section.

00:15:27.840 --> 00:15:32.980
So with this change, and the
amount of meat that people are

00:15:32.980 --> 00:15:36.850
consuming in this country, we've
seen a huge increase in

00:15:36.850 --> 00:15:39.280
the number of animals being
killed for food.

00:15:39.280 --> 00:15:43.170
Now over eight billion, with a
B, farmed animals are killed

00:15:43.170 --> 00:15:45.200
every year in this country.

00:15:45.200 --> 00:15:49.250
This is a graph showing the
slaughter rate of animals.

00:15:49.250 --> 00:15:53.110
Nearly 300 chickens are killed
every single second in this

00:15:53.110 --> 00:15:56.470
country, over three pigs killed
every second, and a cow

00:15:56.470 --> 00:15:58.310
every single second.

00:15:58.310 --> 00:16:01.430
Now, these numbers, none
of us can really grasp.

00:16:01.430 --> 00:16:05.840
As the saying goes, one death
is a tragedy, but a million

00:16:05.840 --> 00:16:09.560
deaths, or in this case eight
billion, is just a statistic.

00:16:09.560 --> 00:16:13.190
It's really difficult for us
to relate to these numbers,

00:16:13.190 --> 00:16:15.300
they're so mind-boggling.

00:16:15.300 --> 00:16:17.715
But it's one, and then one, and
then one, all the way up

00:16:17.715 --> 00:16:20.750
to eight billion.

00:16:20.750 --> 00:16:24.780
So gone are the days of the
idyllic barnyard scenes that

00:16:24.780 --> 00:16:28.930
we grew up with in movies and
our children's books.

00:16:28.930 --> 00:16:32.890
And this is what a modern-day
farm looks like.

00:16:32.890 --> 00:16:34.940
This is a factory egg farm.

00:16:34.940 --> 00:16:38.450
And on this small piece of
property, you can find

00:16:38.450 --> 00:16:43.460
millions of animals intensively
confined.

00:16:43.460 --> 00:16:46.250
This is what most people know
about our current agricultural

00:16:46.250 --> 00:16:47.920
system, nothing.

00:16:47.920 --> 00:16:50.340
They're kept completely
in the dark on how

00:16:50.340 --> 00:16:51.450
these animals are treated.

00:16:51.450 --> 00:16:54.270
And that's because the meat,
dairy, and egg industry spend

00:16:54.270 --> 00:16:56.330
millions and millions of
dollars every year

00:16:56.330 --> 00:17:00.360
spoon-feeding us ads about happy
cows and happy chickens

00:17:00.360 --> 00:17:04.430
to mask the reality of this
institutional and

00:17:04.430 --> 00:17:07.560
industrialized farming system.

00:17:07.560 --> 00:17:09.609
So what we aim to do at Mercy
For Animals with our

00:17:09.609 --> 00:17:12.710
undercover investigations is to
pull back the curtains of

00:17:12.710 --> 00:17:16.010
these facilities, and to shine
a bright spotlight on these

00:17:16.010 --> 00:17:17.260
animals' plights.

00:17:19.270 --> 00:17:21.619
So now in industrial farming, we
see that animals are being

00:17:21.619 --> 00:17:25.180
treated as commodities,
resources, machines, and

00:17:25.180 --> 00:17:27.150
production units.

00:17:27.150 --> 00:17:29.870
This is a quote that appeared
in "National Hog Farmer"

00:17:29.870 --> 00:17:31.925
magazine that said, "the
breeding sow should be thought

00:17:31.925 --> 00:17:35.540
of and treated as a valuable
piece of machinery whose

00:17:35.540 --> 00:17:40.130
function is to pump out baby
pigs like a sausage machine."

00:17:40.130 --> 00:17:42.610
And we see that these
intelligent, sensitive

00:17:42.610 --> 00:17:46.070
creatures have been reduced
to just that, machines.

00:17:46.070 --> 00:17:48.870
They live their lives in tiny
crates where they can't even

00:17:48.870 --> 00:17:52.050
turn around or lie down
comfortably for nearly their

00:17:52.050 --> 00:17:53.630
entire lives.

00:17:53.630 --> 00:17:58.100
They resort to bar-biting,
banging their heads against

00:17:58.100 --> 00:18:01.600
the wire and steel structures
of their cages, because

00:18:01.600 --> 00:18:05.800
they've literally gone insane.

00:18:05.800 --> 00:18:08.630
We've created genetic
Frankensteins chickens.

00:18:08.630 --> 00:18:12.580
On the right here, we have the
modern broiler chicken, named

00:18:12.580 --> 00:18:14.170
literally after the
cooking method.

00:18:14.170 --> 00:18:15.510
These are meat-type birds.

00:18:15.510 --> 00:18:19.860
On the left, we have the
modern-day egg-laying chicken.

00:18:19.860 --> 00:18:22.450
So what we've done is we've
taken these meat-type birds

00:18:22.450 --> 00:18:25.930
and we've bred them to grow so
large so fast that many of

00:18:25.930 --> 00:18:28.200
them can't even withstand
their own body

00:18:28.200 --> 00:18:29.650
weight on their legs.

00:18:29.650 --> 00:18:33.080
Now, back in the 1950s, it
took almost 70 days for a

00:18:33.080 --> 00:18:34.910
chicken to reach
market weight.

00:18:34.910 --> 00:18:38.940
Today, it takes about 47,
in some cases 35.

00:18:38.940 --> 00:18:41.420
They're continuing to chip time
off of these animals'

00:18:41.420 --> 00:18:44.910
lives, and they're reaching
a much larger weight.

00:18:47.570 --> 00:18:49.860
So we essentially have
our baby animals

00:18:49.860 --> 00:18:51.990
in obese adult bodies.

00:18:51.990 --> 00:18:56.180
And what we see is that they
suffer from leg disorders,

00:18:56.180 --> 00:18:59.510
heart and lung failures, and
they're in chronic pain.

00:18:59.510 --> 00:19:03.310
Now, a study found that 90% of
these broiler chickens will

00:19:03.310 --> 00:19:06.210
eat feed that's laced with
painkillers to self-medicate

00:19:06.210 --> 00:19:08.110
themselves, they're in
such chronic pain.

00:19:08.110 --> 00:19:10.260
And the same is true
for turkeys.

00:19:10.260 --> 00:19:12.560
This is a photograph taken
at a Butterball

00:19:12.560 --> 00:19:14.640
facility in North Carolina.

00:19:14.640 --> 00:19:17.870
And this is where the tom
turkeys, or the male turkeys,

00:19:17.870 --> 00:19:18.920
are used for breeding.

00:19:18.920 --> 00:19:21.910
Some of these turkeys
reach 90 pounds.

00:19:21.910 --> 00:19:25.230
They can hardly walk by the time
that they're slaughtered.

00:19:25.230 --> 00:19:29.110
Now, egg-laying chickens have
bred to be smaller birds, but

00:19:29.110 --> 00:19:32.570
to produce an unnaturally
high amount of eggs.

00:19:32.570 --> 00:19:34.930
Now, before we domesticated
these animals, they laid about

00:19:34.930 --> 00:19:36.700
24 eggs a year.

00:19:36.700 --> 00:19:40.250
In the 1950s, they would lay
about 120 eggs a year.

00:19:40.250 --> 00:19:43.680
Today they lay over
200 eggs per year.

00:19:43.680 --> 00:19:46.240
This takes an extreme toll
on their bodies.

00:19:46.240 --> 00:19:48.410
Their calcium is being used to
produce the eggs, so they

00:19:48.410 --> 00:19:51.160
suffer from broken bones
and osteoporosis.

00:19:51.160 --> 00:19:54.030
And this is how 95%
of the hens in

00:19:54.030 --> 00:19:56.300
this country are confined.

00:19:56.300 --> 00:19:59.540
They're kept in cages the size
of a file drawer cabinet, with

00:19:59.540 --> 00:20:01.320
anywhere from five
to seven birds.

00:20:01.320 --> 00:20:02.820
They can't even spread
their wings.

00:20:02.820 --> 00:20:05.550
They can't walk, perch,
roost, dust-bathe.

00:20:05.550 --> 00:20:09.860
They can't do anything that
comes natural to them.

00:20:09.860 --> 00:20:12.835
And then we have cows that are
used for milk production.

00:20:12.835 --> 00:20:15.250
These animals are artificially
inseminated time and time

00:20:15.250 --> 00:20:18.870
again, because cows, like all
other mammals, have to give

00:20:18.870 --> 00:20:20.710
birth in order to lactate.

00:20:20.710 --> 00:20:22.760
So what happens to
these baby cows?

00:20:22.760 --> 00:20:23.580
They're taken away.

00:20:23.580 --> 00:20:25.840
Many of them go into
the veal industry.

00:20:25.840 --> 00:20:28.370
The mothers live like this for
about five years, and then

00:20:28.370 --> 00:20:31.090
they're slaughtered.

00:20:31.090 --> 00:20:35.145
I think this ad poses the
question rather bluntly.

00:20:35.145 --> 00:20:38.810
Do we need to be drinking
cow's milk at all?

00:20:38.810 --> 00:20:42.950
We hear the term that milk
is nature's perfect food.

00:20:42.950 --> 00:20:46.360
And cow's milk is nature's
perfect food, if you're a baby

00:20:46.360 --> 00:20:50.470
calf who's doubling in
size every few weeks.

00:20:50.470 --> 00:20:52.560
But when we think about it,
we're the only species to

00:20:52.560 --> 00:20:54.250
drink milk past infancy.

00:20:54.250 --> 00:20:55.440
We're the only species
to drink the

00:20:55.440 --> 00:20:57.250
milk of another species.

00:20:57.250 --> 00:21:00.340
And this has led to a system
of just absolute horror and

00:21:00.340 --> 00:21:01.610
cruelty for these animals.

00:21:01.610 --> 00:21:04.510
Now, Ruth Harrison, in her book
"Animal Machines," said,

00:21:04.510 --> 00:21:07.380
"if one person is unkind to an
animal, it's considered to be

00:21:07.380 --> 00:21:10.510
cruelty, but where a lot of
people are unkind to animals,

00:21:10.510 --> 00:21:12.770
especially in the name of
commerce, the cruelty is

00:21:12.770 --> 00:21:15.330
condoned and, once sums of money
are at stake, we defend

00:21:15.330 --> 00:21:18.790
it to the last by otherwise
intelligent people."

00:21:18.790 --> 00:21:21.190
And I think that this really
puts into perspective our

00:21:21.190 --> 00:21:26.050
current view and treatment of
animals in this country.

00:21:26.050 --> 00:21:29.780
Polls have been done by Zogby
and Gallup, Ohio State

00:21:29.780 --> 00:21:33.350
University, universities across
the country, that find

00:21:33.350 --> 00:21:36.730
that Americans oppose
animal abuse.

00:21:36.730 --> 00:21:40.700
93% of Americans say animals
deserve protection from

00:21:40.700 --> 00:21:42.130
cruelty, neglect, and abuse.

00:21:42.130 --> 00:21:44.060
93%.

00:21:44.060 --> 00:21:46.620
I challenge you to find any
other issue in this country

00:21:46.620 --> 00:21:49.670
where you can get 93%
of people to agree.

00:21:49.670 --> 00:21:51.610
But when it comes to
animals, we stand

00:21:51.610 --> 00:21:53.690
united in that belief.

00:21:53.690 --> 00:21:57.675
But that belief does not reflect
our actual treatment

00:21:57.675 --> 00:21:59.920
of the majority of animals.

00:21:59.920 --> 00:22:02.890
So I'm going to show a short
four-minute video, and it

00:22:02.890 --> 00:22:06.290
shows what happens on factory
farms and slaughter houses.

00:22:06.290 --> 00:22:09.910
Some of you may find it a bit
disturbing, but I think to be

00:22:09.910 --> 00:22:12.770
ethical consumers, it really
is our obligation to take a

00:22:12.770 --> 00:22:15.181
look at these systems.

00:22:15.181 --> 00:22:18.050
[VIDEO PLAYBACK]

00:22:18.050 --> 00:22:21.440
-In the next few minutes, you
will be given an eye-opening

00:22:21.440 --> 00:22:25.030
look behind the closed doors of
modern farms, hatcheries,

00:22:25.030 --> 00:22:27.210
and slaughter plants, revealing
the journey that

00:22:27.210 --> 00:22:29.373
animals make from
farm to fridge.

00:22:35.360 --> 00:22:38.740
Crowded by the thousands into
filthy sheds, chickens and

00:22:38.740 --> 00:22:41.670
turkeys are denied many of
their most basic natural

00:22:41.670 --> 00:22:44.900
behaviors and needs, such as
fresh air and exercise.

00:22:44.900 --> 00:22:47.854
Sick or injured birds often
have their necks broken.

00:22:52.290 --> 00:22:54.210
Others are clubbed to death.

00:22:54.210 --> 00:22:56.610
At the slaughter plant, the
birds are dumped from their

00:22:56.610 --> 00:23:00.130
crates, then roughly snapped
upside down into moving

00:23:00.130 --> 00:23:02.200
shackles by their
fragile legs.

00:23:02.200 --> 00:23:04.920
From there, the birds are
dragged through an electrified

00:23:04.920 --> 00:23:07.680
vat of water which renders
them paralyzed, but not

00:23:07.680 --> 00:23:08.810
necessarily unconscious.

00:23:08.810 --> 00:23:12.020
They are then pulled across
a blade which slices their

00:23:12.020 --> 00:23:16.530
throats, causing blood to
pour from their necks.

00:23:16.530 --> 00:23:20.240
The egg industry subjects chicks
to horrors few of us

00:23:20.240 --> 00:23:21.490
can even imagine.

00:23:21.490 --> 00:23:24.660
Because male chicks don't lay
eggs and do not grow quickly

00:23:24.660 --> 00:23:27.430
enough to be raised profitably
for meat, they are killed

00:23:27.430 --> 00:23:31.340
within hours after hatching.

00:23:31.340 --> 00:23:34.340
Male chicks are typically thrown
into giant grinding

00:23:34.340 --> 00:23:36.380
machines while still alive.

00:23:36.380 --> 00:23:39.250
Another killing method is to
drop male chicks into trash

00:23:39.250 --> 00:23:41.460
bags to be smothered
or suffocated.

00:23:41.460 --> 00:23:45.320
The females have it even worse,
destined for a life of

00:23:45.320 --> 00:23:47.000
prolonged cruelty.

00:23:47.000 --> 00:23:50.480
To reduce packing induced by
overcrowded living conditions,

00:23:50.480 --> 00:23:54.200
workers use a hot blade or laser
to remove part of the

00:23:54.200 --> 00:23:55.380
chick's beaks.

00:23:55.380 --> 00:23:59.710
This mutilation can cause both
acute and chronic pain.

00:23:59.710 --> 00:24:02.780
After debeaking, the birds are
moved to cages where they will

00:24:02.780 --> 00:24:04.470
spend the rest of their lives.

00:24:04.470 --> 00:24:10.080
Nearly 95% of egg-laying hens
spend their lives confined in

00:24:10.080 --> 00:24:14.530
tiny wire cages like this.

00:24:14.530 --> 00:24:17.380
The majority of today's
dairy cows are

00:24:17.380 --> 00:24:19.970
confined on factory farms.

00:24:19.970 --> 00:24:23.934
Workers subject young cows to
painful mutilations and

00:24:23.934 --> 00:24:25.670
amputations.

00:24:25.670 --> 00:24:29.270
Here, a worker cuts off a cow's
tail, slicing through

00:24:29.270 --> 00:24:32.270
her sensitive skin, nerves,
and bone without any

00:24:32.270 --> 00:24:34.580
painkillers.

00:24:34.580 --> 00:24:38.250
Injuries and illness often
run rampant in filthy,

00:24:38.250 --> 00:24:41.060
disease-ridden factory
farm environments.

00:24:41.060 --> 00:24:44.350
Cows too sick or injured to
stand are called downers, and

00:24:44.350 --> 00:24:46.340
are often left to slowly
suffer and

00:24:46.340 --> 00:24:47.890
die from their injuries.

00:24:47.890 --> 00:24:50.460
Calves on dairy farms are
dragged away from their

00:24:50.460 --> 00:24:53.990
mothers and violently killed,
all so that humans can have

00:24:53.990 --> 00:24:55.240
the milk instead.

00:24:58.200 --> 00:25:02.000
At a fraction of their natural
lifespan, the so-called spent

00:25:02.000 --> 00:25:05.060
dairy cows are prodded onto
transport trucks and shipped

00:25:05.060 --> 00:25:05.960
to slaughter houses.

00:25:05.960 --> 00:25:08.900
-Come on!

00:25:08.900 --> 00:25:12.900
-Unreliable stunning practices
at the slaughterhouse condemn

00:25:12.900 --> 00:25:16.660
many cattle to having their
throats cut and their limbs

00:25:16.660 --> 00:25:18.675
hacked off while still
alive and conscious.

00:25:22.100 --> 00:25:25.380
For nearly their entire
four-month pregnancies, mother

00:25:25.380 --> 00:25:28.700
sows are locked in narrow metal
stalls barely larger

00:25:28.700 --> 00:25:30.480
than their own bodies.

00:25:30.480 --> 00:25:34.070
Soon after birth, piglets are
castrated by workers who cut

00:25:34.070 --> 00:25:38.840
into their skin and rip
out their testicles.

00:25:38.840 --> 00:25:41.580
Next, the workers chop
off their tails.

00:25:41.580 --> 00:25:44.320
