NATHAN RUNKLE: Now, in his
book "Eating Animals,"

00:26:49.020 --> 00:26:53.020
Jonathan Safran Foer spoke to
a number of factory farmers

00:26:53.020 --> 00:26:54.000
about these issues.

00:26:54.000 --> 00:26:57.060
And many of them wanted
to remain anonymous.

00:26:57.060 --> 00:26:58.540
This is a quote from
one of them.

00:26:58.540 --> 00:27:01.960
"What I hate is when consumers
act as if farmers want these

00:27:01.960 --> 00:27:05.490
things, when it's consumers who
tell farmers what to grow.

00:27:05.490 --> 00:27:06.650
They've wanted cheap food.

00:27:06.650 --> 00:27:10.860
We've grown it." And I think
when a lot of people see this

00:27:10.860 --> 00:27:13.790
video, they're angry.

00:27:13.790 --> 00:27:16.120
And a lot of times, they direct
that anger towards the

00:27:16.120 --> 00:27:19.840
individual employees in these
facilities instead of stepping

00:27:19.840 --> 00:27:24.720
back and looking at the system
in a broader, larger view.

00:27:24.720 --> 00:27:27.600
What w found is that, in many
of these factory farm and

00:27:27.600 --> 00:27:30.650
slaughterhouse environments,
the workers are victims of

00:27:30.650 --> 00:27:34.590
this system in much the same
way as the animals are.

00:27:34.590 --> 00:27:36.260
Many of them are undocumented
workers.

00:27:36.260 --> 00:27:38.110
They take this work because
it's the only

00:27:38.110 --> 00:27:39.150
work they can find.

00:27:39.150 --> 00:27:40.950
They work long hours.

00:27:40.950 --> 00:27:43.660
And what we see is that many
of them are very troubled

00:27:43.660 --> 00:27:46.060
initially by what
they see there.

00:27:46.060 --> 00:27:48.760
And in fact, there have been
studies done that find that

00:27:48.760 --> 00:27:52.090
many slaughterhouse and factory
farm workers suffer

00:27:52.090 --> 00:27:54.340
from what's called
perpetration-induced traumatic

00:27:54.340 --> 00:27:56.520
stress disorder, which is
essentially a form of

00:27:56.520 --> 00:28:00.170
post-traumatic stress disorder
that comes about when people

00:28:00.170 --> 00:28:05.180
are put in situations to do
things that they find morally

00:28:05.180 --> 00:28:06.420
unacceptable.

00:28:06.420 --> 00:28:09.860
We saw this in some situations
with Nazis and executioners,

00:28:09.860 --> 00:28:12.040
people that are in
war environments.

00:28:12.040 --> 00:28:14.850
We're seeing the same thing in
factory farm workers and

00:28:14.850 --> 00:28:16.020
slaughterhouse workers.

00:28:16.020 --> 00:28:19.110
And as a result, we see
increased levels of alcohol

00:28:19.110 --> 00:28:20.510
and drug abuse.

00:28:20.510 --> 00:28:25.070
We see increased numbers of
domestic violence disputes.

00:28:25.070 --> 00:28:27.430
So I think we have to ask
ourselves, if this system is

00:28:27.430 --> 00:28:31.210
so unpleasant and violent
and cruel that it causes

00:28:31.210 --> 00:28:33.210
psychological distress and
damage to the people that have

00:28:33.210 --> 00:28:35.900
to work in them, what does that
say about the practice?

00:28:35.900 --> 00:28:38.590
And is that something that we
should be supporting in a

00:28:38.590 --> 00:28:40.590
civilized society?

00:28:40.590 --> 00:28:43.510
The other thing that people say
is, this footage must be

00:28:43.510 --> 00:28:46.000
old, this must be out of the
United States, this couldn't

00:28:46.000 --> 00:28:49.110
possibly be happening
in the 21st century.

00:28:49.110 --> 00:28:51.935
We have laws and regulations
for everything, right?

00:28:51.935 --> 00:28:54.755
Well, unfortunately pretty much
all of this footage that

00:28:54.755 --> 00:28:57.310
you saw was taken in the
last five years alone

00:28:57.310 --> 00:28:58.380
in the United States.

00:28:58.380 --> 00:29:02.040
This is just a snapshot
of the treatment

00:29:02.040 --> 00:29:03.520
these animals endure.

00:29:03.520 --> 00:29:05.560
So what do the laws look
like in this country?

00:29:05.560 --> 00:29:07.850
Well, unfortunately they
don't look very

00:29:07.850 --> 00:29:10.480
promising for farmed animals.

00:29:10.480 --> 00:29:12.890
We have a system where
agribusiness is so large and

00:29:12.890 --> 00:29:15.350
powerful that they've been able
to lobby so that state

00:29:15.350 --> 00:29:17.060
and federal laws are written
in a way that

00:29:17.060 --> 00:29:19.410
exempt farmed animals.

00:29:19.410 --> 00:29:22.160
So on a federal level, we see
that there's not a single

00:29:22.160 --> 00:29:25.410
federal law that provides
protection to farmed animals

00:29:25.410 --> 00:29:27.710
during their lives
on factory farms.

00:29:27.710 --> 00:29:31.330
There is a federal law for
transport and slaughter for

00:29:31.330 --> 00:29:34.450
mammals, but it totally exempts
birds, which make up

00:29:34.450 --> 00:29:38.900
over 95% of the animals used
for food production.

00:29:38.900 --> 00:29:41.550
So for the majority of these
animals' lives, no protection

00:29:41.550 --> 00:29:42.520
on the federal level.

00:29:42.520 --> 00:29:44.770
The Humane Methods of Slaughter
Act exempt birds,

00:29:44.770 --> 00:29:47.420
which means that many of them
have their throats slit and go

00:29:47.420 --> 00:29:50.340
into the scalding tanks while
they're still alive.

00:29:50.340 --> 00:29:53.720
Now, all 50 states have
anti-cruelty laws, varying in

00:29:53.720 --> 00:29:55.820
scope and definition.

00:29:55.820 --> 00:30:00.400
But most of them completely
exempt or largely exempt farm

00:30:00.400 --> 00:30:02.280
animals from their protection.

00:30:02.280 --> 00:30:05.190
So similar to the case that I
described earlier about the

00:30:05.190 --> 00:30:07.820
piglet being slammed into the
ground, we see that other

00:30:07.820 --> 00:30:11.490
routine practices that cause
extreme suffering for animals

00:30:11.490 --> 00:30:13.960
are allowed to happen on
a state level as well.

00:30:13.960 --> 00:30:16.940
Things like inflicting
third-degree burns on animals

00:30:16.940 --> 00:30:19.730
that are conscious without
painkillers is deemed legal

00:30:19.730 --> 00:30:21.170
because of exemptions.

00:30:21.170 --> 00:30:24.700
Castrating piglets, legal
without painkillers because of

00:30:24.700 --> 00:30:25.340
exemptions.

00:30:25.340 --> 00:30:28.590
Now, to put this into context,
if you had a puppy that you

00:30:28.590 --> 00:30:31.730
took to your local vet and
said, I'm here to have my

00:30:31.730 --> 00:30:34.960
puppy neutered, and your vet
took your puppy by his hind

00:30:34.960 --> 00:30:38.130
legs, held him up, took out a
scalpel, cut him open, ripped

00:30:38.130 --> 00:30:41.060
out his testicles and hand the
puppy back to you, you

00:30:41.060 --> 00:30:44.410
probably wouldn't be very
thrilled or excited with your

00:30:44.410 --> 00:30:47.950
vet visit, and you'd probably
call law enforcement, and that

00:30:47.950 --> 00:30:50.180
vet would probably be shut
down for malpractice and

00:30:50.180 --> 00:30:52.040
charged with animal cruelty.

00:30:52.040 --> 00:30:54.960
But we do this to piglets
every single day.

00:30:54.960 --> 00:30:56.690
And these aren't even vets
that are doing this.

00:30:56.690 --> 00:30:59.230
These are untrained, unskilled
workers working

00:30:59.230 --> 00:31:01.270
at an alarming rate.

00:31:01.270 --> 00:31:04.070
And then we have things like
cutting the beaks off of

00:31:04.070 --> 00:31:05.450
chickens without
any painkillers

00:31:05.450 --> 00:31:06.850
also allowed to happen.

00:31:06.850 --> 00:31:09.740
So we've handed the power to
decide what is cruelty and

00:31:09.740 --> 00:31:12.860
what is acceptable to the very
industries that profit off of

00:31:12.860 --> 00:31:14.470
using these animals
themselves.

00:31:14.470 --> 00:31:16.090
And it hasn't worked.

00:31:16.090 --> 00:31:18.640
Now, the good news is that we're
starting to see some

00:31:18.640 --> 00:31:21.520
change on this issue
as consumers

00:31:21.520 --> 00:31:24.220
wake up to these practices.

00:31:24.220 --> 00:31:27.720
In 2008, California passed
Proposition 2.

00:31:27.720 --> 00:31:31.210
And Proposition 2 was a modest
yet meaningful initiative that

00:31:31.210 --> 00:31:35.510
said that calves raised for
veal, pregnant pigs, and

00:31:35.510 --> 00:31:38.160
egg-laying hens had to be given
enough space to stand

00:31:38.160 --> 00:31:42.300
up, turn around, lie down,
and extend their limbs.

00:31:42.300 --> 00:31:45.230
Now, that ballot initiative
passed by an

00:31:45.230 --> 00:31:47.110
overwhelming majority.

00:31:47.110 --> 00:31:50.770
63% of California voters
passed Proposition 2.

00:31:50.770 --> 00:31:54.960
More people voted for Prop 2 in
2008 than voted for Obama

00:31:54.960 --> 00:31:56.640
in California.

00:31:56.640 --> 00:32:01.270
And this law really helped
set a precedent.

00:32:01.270 --> 00:32:05.560
Since then, we've had nine
states pass laws banning these

00:32:05.560 --> 00:32:08.140
tiny gestation crates for
breeding pigs, a number of

00:32:08.140 --> 00:32:11.300
states banning battery cages for
egg-laying hens and veal

00:32:11.300 --> 00:32:14.110
crates, also being outlawed.

00:32:14.110 --> 00:32:16.160
But there's still much
work to be done.

00:32:16.160 --> 00:32:18.060
Now, I want to tell
you a quick story

00:32:18.060 --> 00:32:18.960
about this man here.

00:32:18.960 --> 00:32:20.950
His name is Virgil Butler.

00:32:20.950 --> 00:32:24.870
Virgil Butler worked for almost
10 years in a Tyson

00:32:24.870 --> 00:32:26.830
slaughterhouse in Arkansas.

00:32:26.830 --> 00:32:31.000
And Virgil's job was to take
birds as they arrived in

00:32:31.000 --> 00:32:33.790
crates and snap them into those
moving conveyor belts

00:32:33.790 --> 00:32:34.990
that you just saw.

00:32:34.990 --> 00:32:39.370
Now, Virgil witnessed a lot of
abuse, not only the standard

00:32:39.370 --> 00:32:41.990
mistreatment of these animals,
but he witnessed his

00:32:41.990 --> 00:32:44.640
co-workers stomping on birds,
ripping their heads off,

00:32:44.640 --> 00:32:47.170
putting ice bombs in them and
watching them explode on the

00:32:47.170 --> 00:32:48.400
slaughter line.

00:32:48.400 --> 00:32:51.870
And over time, Virgil started
to become very disturbed by

00:32:51.870 --> 00:32:52.780
what he saw.

00:32:52.780 --> 00:32:54.880
He started having nightmares.

00:32:54.880 --> 00:32:57.850
And he said, I can't
be involved in

00:32:57.850 --> 00:32:59.900
this system any longer.

00:32:59.900 --> 00:33:02.180
So Virgil quit his job.

00:33:02.180 --> 00:33:04.550
He had no real financial
backing.

00:33:04.550 --> 00:33:07.080
This is his trailer that he
lived in behind him, in this

00:33:07.080 --> 00:33:08.030
photograph.

00:33:08.030 --> 00:33:10.130
And he went vegan,
and he became an

00:33:10.130 --> 00:33:11.000
animal rights activists.

00:33:11.000 --> 00:33:13.930
And he started blogging about
what he saw, not only to

00:33:13.930 --> 00:33:16.530
expose the abuse, but as
self-therapy as well.

00:33:16.530 --> 00:33:20.010
And he started traveling the
country, sharing his firsthand

00:33:20.010 --> 00:33:21.760
experiences with others.

00:33:21.760 --> 00:33:24.870
So I think that Virgil is one
of many examples of someone

00:33:24.870 --> 00:33:29.490
who can be so invested and
involved in this system, but

00:33:29.490 --> 00:33:33.930
can still be in touch with that
greater good that he has,

00:33:33.930 --> 00:33:35.630
that spark of humanity.

00:33:35.630 --> 00:33:37.270
And he has made changes.

00:33:37.270 --> 00:33:39.950
And I think that if Virgil can
do this, any of us, no matter

00:33:39.950 --> 00:33:43.160
where we are in our current
lives, can make changes, can

00:33:43.160 --> 00:33:46.950
take steps to become
more compassionate.

00:33:46.950 --> 00:33:50.860
Now, we live in an era where
our forks and knives have

00:33:50.860 --> 00:33:53.640
become, really, weapons
of mass destruction.

00:33:53.640 --> 00:33:56.990
We can use them for compassion
and kindness for animals, or

00:33:56.990 --> 00:33:58.400
cruelty and exploitation.

00:34:01.880 --> 00:34:05.310
Now, I think if these were eight
billion dogs or cats

00:34:05.310 --> 00:34:07.840
that were being subjected to
these conditions, there would

00:34:07.840 --> 00:34:10.210
be such a public outcry.

00:34:10.210 --> 00:34:12.530
And we should have that same
level of outcry for farmed

00:34:12.530 --> 00:34:13.980
animals as well.

00:34:13.980 --> 00:34:16.469
Now, "The Economist" put it
well, I think, when they said,

00:34:16.469 --> 00:34:19.060
"few people would keep a hen in
a shoe box for her entire

00:34:19.060 --> 00:34:22.670
egg-laying life; but practically
everyone will eat

00:34:22.670 --> 00:34:27.880
smartly packaged, 'farm fresh'
eggs from battery hens." Few

00:34:27.880 --> 00:34:30.800
of us in good conscience would
treat these animals in the way

00:34:30.800 --> 00:34:33.620
that you've seen
this afternoon.

00:34:33.620 --> 00:34:35.730
But when we go to the
supermarket and we buy these

00:34:35.730 --> 00:34:39.679
products, we're essentially
hiring someone to do this

00:34:39.679 --> 00:34:41.960
dirty work on our behalf.

00:34:41.960 --> 00:34:45.050
So we have to ask ourselves,
do we feel comfortable

00:34:45.050 --> 00:34:46.699
supporting this abuse
financially?

00:34:46.699 --> 00:34:48.759
Because that's what we're doing,
is we're financing it.

00:34:48.759 --> 00:34:52.570
Now, our food choices
have a huge impact.

00:34:52.570 --> 00:34:57.740
The average American eats about
2,700 land animals in

00:34:57.740 --> 00:34:58.730
their lifetime.

00:34:58.730 --> 00:35:03.030
So by making some dietary
changes, by eliminating meat

00:35:03.030 --> 00:35:05.830
on Mondays, or reducing our meat
consumption, becoming a

00:35:05.830 --> 00:35:10.050
flexitarian, or becoming a
full-blown vegan, we can help

00:35:10.050 --> 00:35:11.850
spare animals this suffering.

00:35:11.850 --> 00:35:13.870
And this is an illustration
showing

00:35:13.870 --> 00:35:14.690
those number of animals.

00:35:14.690 --> 00:35:18.000
And we really are at a
critical juncture.

00:35:18.000 --> 00:35:20.720
We're at a time when not only
is animal abuse rampant in

00:35:20.720 --> 00:35:23.490
this industry, but the
environmental impact of animal

00:35:23.490 --> 00:35:27.105
agriculture is very extreme
and severe.

00:35:27.105 --> 00:35:30.250
The United Nations published
a report, "Livestock's Long

00:35:30.250 --> 00:35:33.500
Shadow," that found that
animal agriculture is

00:35:33.500 --> 00:35:36.840
responsible for the release of
more greenhouse gases than the

00:35:36.840 --> 00:35:40.430
entire transportation
sector combined.

00:35:40.430 --> 00:35:44.620
18% of greenhouse gases are
associated with the livestock

00:35:44.620 --> 00:35:51.360
sector, so more so than cars,
trains, automobiles combined.

00:35:51.360 --> 00:35:54.150
So not only are we wreaking
havoc on animals and the

00:35:54.150 --> 00:35:58.040
environment, but also to
our own health as well.

00:35:58.040 --> 00:36:01.250
And that's what's led the UN
to say that we should be

00:36:01.250 --> 00:36:06.170
eating less meat to curb
global warming.

00:36:06.170 --> 00:36:07.980
And we see that it's not just
global warming, but it's a

00:36:07.980 --> 00:36:09.290
waste of resources.

00:36:09.290 --> 00:36:13.090
We have to use so much water,
which is a scarce commodity,

00:36:13.090 --> 00:36:16.380
and growing scarcer now
across the globe.

00:36:16.380 --> 00:36:19.960
We see that we're funneling so
much grain into animals to get

00:36:19.960 --> 00:36:22.995
a relatively small amount
of meat in return.

00:36:22.995 --> 00:36:26.560
Now, this is an article that
appeared all over the country

00:36:26.560 --> 00:36:30.670
recently, but this particular
