condemn us for?

00:38:27.490 --> 00:38:30.180
And they found that second only
to our treatment of the

00:38:30.180 --> 00:38:34.150
environment is our treatment of
animals in food production.

00:38:34.150 --> 00:38:37.040
So I think that this is a
generational issue, like so

00:38:37.040 --> 00:38:39.230
many social issues are.

00:38:39.230 --> 00:38:41.260
And this is one of our time.

00:38:41.260 --> 00:38:44.980
We have billions of animals that
are being subjected to

00:38:44.980 --> 00:38:46.880
horrors beyond belief.

00:38:46.880 --> 00:38:49.890
And I think that future
generations will ask us, what

00:38:49.890 --> 00:38:52.600
did we do to right this wrong?

00:38:52.600 --> 00:38:56.590
I think that animal protection
is a social justice movement.

00:38:56.590 --> 00:38:59.050
Based on the number of
individuals that are suffering

00:38:59.050 --> 00:39:00.700
and the degree of their
suffering, I think it's one of

00:39:00.700 --> 00:39:02.730
the most pressing of our time.

00:39:02.730 --> 00:39:05.310
Unlike other social justice
movements, where those that

00:39:05.310 --> 00:39:08.500
are being oppressed had a
voice in society to some

00:39:08.500 --> 00:39:11.280
degree-- they could protest,
they could lobby, they could

00:39:11.280 --> 00:39:12.910
ask for boycotts--

00:39:12.910 --> 00:39:14.210
these animals can't do that.

00:39:14.210 --> 00:39:16.540
Now, you saw in this video
of factory farms and

00:39:16.540 --> 00:39:19.580
slaughterhouses that these
animals kick and scream.

00:39:19.580 --> 00:39:21.710
They struggle and fight against
their oppressors to

00:39:21.710 --> 00:39:23.230
the best of their ability.

00:39:23.230 --> 00:39:27.430
But they do rely on each and
every one of us to speak out

00:39:27.430 --> 00:39:31.350
on their behalf within our
society and culture.

00:39:31.350 --> 00:39:35.990
We are in a situation where
we hold all of the power.

00:39:35.990 --> 00:39:38.320
And these animals are completely
at our mercy.

00:39:38.320 --> 00:39:41.970
Now, what we do with that power
is totally up to us.

00:39:41.970 --> 00:39:44.330
And with power comes
responsibility.

00:39:44.330 --> 00:39:47.570
And as Harriet Beecher Stowe
said, "it's a matter of taking

00:39:47.570 --> 00:39:50.670
the side of the weak against the
strong, something the best

00:39:50.670 --> 00:39:53.760
people have always done." And I
think it's hard to imagine a

00:39:53.760 --> 00:39:56.770
group of individuals that are
weaker and more vulnerable

00:39:56.770 --> 00:39:57.460
than farmed animals.

00:39:57.460 --> 00:40:00.550
So I encourage you to take the
side of the weak against the

00:40:00.550 --> 00:40:03.680
strong, and make decisions and
take actions that will help

00:40:03.680 --> 00:40:05.730
bring compassion and
justice to them.

00:40:05.730 --> 00:40:06.985
Thank you so much.

00:40:06.985 --> 00:40:13.290
[APPLAUSE]

00:40:13.290 --> 00:40:15.800
NATHAN RUNKLE: I think we have
time for some questions if

00:40:15.800 --> 00:40:17.050
anyone has any.

00:40:20.770 --> 00:40:24.620
Yeah, so Europe, I would say, is
about 10 years ahead of the

00:40:24.620 --> 00:40:28.910
US in terms of addressing farm
animal protection issues.

00:40:28.910 --> 00:40:32.810
They, in some cases about 10
years ago, started banning

00:40:32.810 --> 00:40:37.680
veal crates, battery cages,
gestation crates.

00:40:37.680 --> 00:40:40.440
And some of those are now taking
effect, some of them

00:40:40.440 --> 00:40:42.800
last year, some of
them next year.

00:40:42.800 --> 00:40:45.840
So yes, they're starting to
address those issues.

00:40:45.840 --> 00:40:49.000
Now, we have other countries,
unfortunately, more developing

00:40:49.000 --> 00:40:52.400
countries like India, that for
the longest time sort of held

00:40:52.400 --> 00:40:56.150
as its root belief that animals
deserved compassion.

00:40:56.150 --> 00:40:59.460
Now we're seeing factory farm
interests, McDonald's, Burger

00:40:59.460 --> 00:41:01.860
King, Wendy's, coming into
these countries.

00:41:01.860 --> 00:41:04.690
And meat consumption is
dramatically rising.

00:41:04.690 --> 00:41:06.360
And with that, we see
factory farming

00:41:06.360 --> 00:41:07.970
coming into those countries.

00:41:07.970 --> 00:41:10.400
So for example, in India,
there's as many hens in

00:41:10.400 --> 00:41:12.550
battery cages in India
as there are in the

00:41:12.550 --> 00:41:14.040
United States now.

00:41:14.040 --> 00:41:17.030
So we see some countries that
are leading the way and ahead

00:41:17.030 --> 00:41:19.470
of us, and then we have others
that are actually just sort of

00:41:19.470 --> 00:41:21.300
catching up with factory
farming.

00:41:21.300 --> 00:41:24.550
So it's an issue that needs
to be addressed globally.

00:41:29.450 --> 00:41:33.040
Yeah, I don't know all the
specifics of their other

00:41:33.040 --> 00:41:34.630
economics there.

00:41:34.630 --> 00:41:40.490
But one issue is, you can look
at grids and you can see just

00:41:40.490 --> 00:41:43.550
how meat consumption has
dramatically increased in the

00:41:43.550 --> 00:41:44.240
United States.

00:41:44.240 --> 00:41:47.440
Now, the good news is, since
2007, meat consumption in the

00:41:47.440 --> 00:41:50.320
US has started to decline,
really for the first time.

00:41:50.320 --> 00:41:53.700
We're now killing about 400
million fewer farm animals

00:41:53.700 --> 00:41:55.850
than we were in 2007.

00:41:55.850 --> 00:42:00.060
That's about a 12% decline.

00:42:00.060 --> 00:42:03.770
In Latin America, my guess would
be that they're probably

00:42:03.770 --> 00:42:06.610
eating more cows than
they are chickens.

00:42:06.610 --> 00:42:10.310
And those are animals that you
can have out in a grazing area

00:42:10.310 --> 00:42:14.170
more, which costs less than
these intensive factory farm

00:42:14.170 --> 00:42:15.420
systems would.

00:42:19.940 --> 00:42:22.680
It's a great question.

00:42:22.680 --> 00:42:25.110
Sort of like the quote from the
anonymous factory farmer,

00:42:25.110 --> 00:42:28.950
it's not that farmers are run by
a bunch of sadistic people.

00:42:28.950 --> 00:42:31.370
These are people that respond to
the marketplace and supply

00:42:31.370 --> 00:42:33.260
and demand.

00:42:33.260 --> 00:42:37.440
So we see the plant-based food
market just dramatically

00:42:37.440 --> 00:42:40.810
exploding as people become
more aware of it.

00:42:40.810 --> 00:42:42.130
Bill Gates actually--

00:42:42.130 --> 00:42:44.680
this is not a joke--

00:42:44.680 --> 00:42:47.060
recently said that, really,
the future of food is in

00:42:47.060 --> 00:42:50.270
plant-based proteins and
things-- again, looking at the

00:42:50.270 --> 00:42:52.490
environmental impact,
the cruelty issues.

00:42:52.490 --> 00:42:54.210
So I think we're going to
see more of that grow.

00:42:54.210 --> 00:42:58.980
In terms of these cage-free,
free-range, so-called humane

00:42:58.980 --> 00:43:01.330
meat products, it's a
business decision.

00:43:01.330 --> 00:43:04.550
But ultimately I think it's a
business decision that is

00:43:04.550 --> 00:43:06.400
helping animals to
some extent.

00:43:06.400 --> 00:43:09.700
They're getting them out of
these really intensive

00:43:09.700 --> 00:43:11.160
confinement systems.

00:43:11.160 --> 00:43:15.050
But I don't think that the
typical cage-free or

00:43:15.050 --> 00:43:18.850
free-range egg facility looks
like what most people think it

00:43:18.850 --> 00:43:21.200
should look like, because you're
absolutely right--

00:43:21.200 --> 00:43:25.340
they're the same big-interest,
the big factory farms that are

00:43:25.340 --> 00:43:26.510
producing these eggs.

00:43:26.510 --> 00:43:28.380
And we've done investigations
at these places.

00:43:28.380 --> 00:43:31.220
They'll have one shed on the
same property that are battery

00:43:31.220 --> 00:43:34.400
cages, and the next shed will
be the cage-free eggs.

00:43:34.400 --> 00:43:37.740
And they'll have literally tens
of thousands of birds in

00:43:37.740 --> 00:43:40.220
windowless sheds.

00:43:40.220 --> 00:43:42.280
They're not in cages, which
is an improvement.

00:43:42.280 --> 00:43:43.880
Some of them have perches.

00:43:43.880 --> 00:43:47.260
They can walk around, but
they're not frolicking out in

00:43:47.260 --> 00:43:49.730
the field like most people
would imagine.

00:43:49.730 --> 00:43:54.420
So I think it's progress, but
it's certainly not perfection.

00:43:54.420 --> 00:43:58.130
And I think, overall, we need to
at least be decreasing the

00:43:58.130 --> 00:44:00.020
amount of animal products
that we're using.

00:44:04.160 --> 00:44:06.230
It's about efficiency.

00:44:06.230 --> 00:44:07.930
These are factory farms.

00:44:07.930 --> 00:44:09.360
They're the model
of efficiency.

00:44:09.360 --> 00:44:14.210
And if they can mechanize
everything and have animals in

00:44:14.210 --> 00:44:18.830
a smaller area, it takes less
labor to get the job done.

00:44:18.830 --> 00:44:23.260
It takes less heating
and electricity to

00:44:23.260 --> 00:44:25.130
operate those units .

00:44:25.130 --> 00:44:26.625
So it's all about efficiency.

00:44:26.625 --> 00:44:29.040
I mean, certainly there's
land available

00:44:29.040 --> 00:44:30.290
to give these animals.

00:44:36.410 --> 00:44:39.040
I don't think that the world
or life is ever in

00:44:39.040 --> 00:44:41.470
black-and-white terms, and
we understand that.

00:44:41.470 --> 00:44:44.970
Now, we certainly think that
a vegan diet is, in most

00:44:44.970 --> 00:44:48.640
situations, the most ethical,
compassionate, environmentally

00:44:48.640 --> 00:44:50.480
friendly choice that
we can make.

00:44:50.480 --> 00:44:52.825
So of course we hold that
as the gold standard.

00:44:52.825 --> 00:44:56.930
But we understand that there are
gradations along the lines

00:44:56.930 --> 00:44:57.910
of agriculture.

00:44:57.910 --> 00:45:00.880
We have intensive factory
farm systems, which is

00:45:00.880 --> 00:45:04.055
unfortunately how the vast
majority of food is produced.

00:45:04.055 --> 00:45:06.390
It's like I said, 95%
of egg-laying hens.

00:45:06.390 --> 00:45:09.040
We've got pretty much all
the broiler chickens.

00:45:09.040 --> 00:45:12.160
About 80% of pigs are
intensively confined.

00:45:12.160 --> 00:45:13.750
This is the gold standard.

00:45:13.750 --> 00:45:16.925
These other situations are such,
really, the monopoly

00:45:16.925 --> 00:45:19.950
that you have to go out
of your way to find.

00:45:19.950 --> 00:45:22.700
So we think people need to know
what the choices are.

00:45:22.700 --> 00:45:26.250
But is a cow that's lived out
her entire life in pasture and

00:45:26.250 --> 00:45:28.960
then was killed on the farm
better than a factory farm?

00:45:28.960 --> 00:45:31.610
Absolutely, it's better.

00:45:31.610 --> 00:45:35.280
Do I think that we should be
killing the cow rather than

00:45:35.280 --> 00:45:36.480
eating carrots?

00:45:36.480 --> 00:45:37.790
Probably the carrots
is a better

00:45:37.790 --> 00:45:39.610
choice for me, ethically.

00:45:39.610 --> 00:45:41.540
If I don't have to take
a life and be

00:45:41.540 --> 00:45:44.040
violent, probably wouldn't.

00:45:44.040 --> 00:45:47.410
But there are people that just
don't share that belief.

00:45:47.410 --> 00:45:51.230
And I think for them, doing,
again, as little harm and as

00:45:51.230 --> 00:45:53.200
much good as possible is really
what we should be

00:45:53.200 --> 00:45:53.660
looking at.

00:45:53.660 --> 00:45:58.900
And certainly, whether you're
a die-hard meat-eater or a

00:45:58.900 --> 00:46:01.820
vegan, we can all probably agree
that this factory farm

00:46:01.820 --> 00:46:04.950
system just doesn't fall
into line with what

00:46:04.950 --> 00:46:06.200
is ethical for us.

00:46:10.750 --> 00:46:12.730
Yeah, it's true.

00:46:12.730 --> 00:46:15.540
A lot of these animals still go
to the same slaughterhouse.

00:46:15.540 --> 00:46:17.060
Some of them are killed
on the farm.

00:46:17.060 --> 00:46:19.940
But again, that's such
a small percentage.

00:46:19.940 --> 00:46:22.250
So yes, a lot of them go to
the same slaughterhouses.

00:46:22.250 --> 00:46:25.480
For egg-laying hens, most of the
chicks still come from the

00:46:25.480 --> 00:46:26.260
same hatcheries.

00:46:26.260 --> 00:46:28.560
So all the male chicks are
still ground up alive.

00:46:28.560 --> 00:46:30.930
They still have their
beaks cut off.

00:46:30.930 --> 00:46:37.050
So there are built-in, I think,
moral issues that we

00:46:37.050 --> 00:46:39.970
have to look at with animal
agriculture to begin with.

00:46:39.970 --> 00:46:41.910
And those are things that we
have to sort of come to terms

00:46:41.910 --> 00:46:45.590
with what we're comfortable
with.

00:46:45.590 --> 00:46:48.420
There is an amount of domination
and exploitation

00:46:48.420 --> 00:46:49.310
that's involved in any

00:46:49.310 --> 00:46:52.810
agricultural system, of course.

00:46:52.810 --> 00:46:54.430
So you're absolutely right.

00:46:54.430 --> 00:46:57.740
I think it does boil down to,
are we OK with some amount of

00:46:57.740 --> 00:47:00.590
violence to animals for food,
or do we just want to remove

00:47:00.590 --> 00:47:02.590
ourselves completely
from that system?

00:47:02.590 --> 00:47:04.850
I've chosen to remove myself
from that system.

00:47:04.850 --> 00:47:08.470
But to say that all farms are
exactly the same I think

00:47:08.470 --> 00:47:10.900
probably oversimplifies
the issue a bit.

00:47:10.900 --> 00:47:13.360
But those are things that we
should all just be aware of as

00:47:13.360 --> 00:47:14.610
conscious consumers, yeah.

00:47:20.010 --> 00:47:22.330
Yeah, it's a great question.

00:47:22.330 --> 00:47:26.490
And a big part of why meat,
dairy, and egg products are so

00:47:26.490 --> 00:47:29.460
cheap is because they're
subsidized by the government.

00:47:29.460 --> 00:47:32.210
If we were actually paying the
true cost, those products

00:47:32.210 --> 00:47:33.740
would be much higher.

00:47:33.740 --> 00:47:36.290
So I think that's a whole issue
that we really need to

00:47:36.290 --> 00:47:39.770
take a critical look at.

00:47:39.770 --> 00:47:43.760
But there's obviously a vegan
diet that can be very

00:47:43.760 --> 00:47:46.310
expensive, that you're
eating a lot of niche

00:47:46.310 --> 00:47:48.430
meat-alternative products
that are made.

00:47:48.430 --> 00:47:52.400
And then you can have one that
is based more on beans and

00:47:52.400 --> 00:47:55.530
nuts and legumes and vegetables
and things that

00:47:55.530 --> 00:47:57.210
can, in some situations,
actually be

00:47:57.210 --> 00:47:59.630
cheaper to eat that way.

00:47:59.630 --> 00:48:03.330
But in terms of addressing this,
there are a number of

00:48:03.330 --> 00:48:05.960
companies now-- one
is Beyond Meat--

00:48:05.960 --> 00:48:09.220
that is looking to make
meat-alternative products that

00:48:09.220 --> 00:48:13.250
are cheaper than meat
products are.

00:48:13.250 --> 00:48:17.800
They have no fat, no
cholesterol, high protein,

00:48:17.800 --> 00:48:20.420
really being innovative in
addressing these issues.

00:48:20.420 --> 00:48:22.240
And then some of it is
supply and demand.

00:48:22.240 --> 00:48:24.330
And the more it's a niche
market, the more it's going to

00:48:24.330 --> 00:48:26.540
cost to create each unit.

00:48:26.540 --> 00:48:30.045
So I think that there's
sort of a number

00:48:30.045 --> 00:48:30.990
of answers to that.

00:48:30.990 --> 00:48:39.010
But again, I think that
Americans, and just our whole

00:48:39.010 --> 00:48:42.440
humanity, really, have proven
time and again that we can be

00:48:42.440 --> 00:48:44.500
creative in solving
a lot of problems.

00:48:44.500 --> 00:48:46.700
I think Google is a great
example of doing things that

00:48:46.700 --> 00:48:49.530
people once thought
were unheard of.

00:48:49.530 --> 00:48:52.620
This is an issue where I think
if we put the time and

00:48:52.620 --> 00:48:56.840
attention and resources, it can
be solved rather quickly.

00:48:56.840 --> 00:49:00.650
And I think we're starting to
see, in some ways, capitalism

00:49:00.650 --> 00:49:04.070
and these inventive companies
starting to jump in and

00:49:04.070 --> 00:49:05.320
address it as well.

00:49:10.310 --> 00:49:12.400
So we have a multi-prong
approach.

00:49:12.400 --> 00:49:16.640
Again, these are complicated,
deeply rooted issues.

00:49:16.640 --> 00:49:20.080
So to say that there is a
one-size-fit-all answer that's

00:49:20.080 --> 00:49:22.770
going to address this in any
sort of timely manner I think

00:49:22.770 --> 00:49:24.820
is probably oversimplifying
it a bit.

00:49:24.820 --> 00:49:27.410
So that's why we have the four
areas that we work in,

00:49:27.410 --> 00:49:30.680
education being a large
component of that.

00:49:30.680 --> 00:49:32.520
Getting people to see what's
really going on and

00:49:32.520 --> 00:49:35.310
encouraging them to reduce or,
ideally, eliminating their

00:49:35.310 --> 00:49:38.100
meat, dairy, egg consumption,
that's really the root cause

00:49:38.100 --> 00:49:39.500
of all of this, obviously.

00:49:39.500 --> 00:49:41.970
But we understand that the
world is not going to go

00:49:41.970 --> 00:49:45.280
vegetarian or vegan, certainly
not overnight.

00:49:45.280 --> 00:49:47.640
And we think that these animals
that are here right

00:49:47.640 --> 00:49:51.550
now, suffering as individuals
with needs and interests,

00:49:51.550 --> 00:49:56.030
deserve to be treated with as
much care as we can give them.

00:49:56.030 --> 00:50:00.480
That being said, changes happen
slowly over time.

00:50:00.480 --> 00:50:04.620
So we view banning some of the
worst factory farm practices,

00:50:04.620 --> 00:50:06.935
like these battery cages for
egg-laying hens, where they

00:50:06.935 --> 00:50:08.980
can't spread their wings, or
gestation crates for sows,

00:50:08.980 --> 00:50:11.510
where they can't turn around,
or tail-docking, cutting the

00:50:11.510 --> 00:50:14.230
tails off these animals without
painkillers, as being

00:50:14.230 --> 00:50:17.630
really unethical practices that
we should be moving to

00:50:17.630 --> 00:50:21.450
end right now, and that we can
start to reduce the amount of

00:50:21.450 --> 00:50:24.170
suffering that these animals
are subjected to, because

00:50:24.170 --> 00:50:26.500
these are real animals,
real lives, the stakes

00:50:26.500 --> 00:50:27.870
are real for them.

00:50:27.870 --> 00:50:30.700
And though giving them a few
more inches of space might not

00:50:30.700 --> 00:50:33.080
solve all the problems-- and we
certainly don't think that

00:50:33.080 --> 00:50:34.280
that is the case--

00:50:34.280 --> 00:50:38.010
we do think that it reduces
the sum total of suffering

00:50:38.010 --> 00:50:42.020
that they're subjected to, as we
move towards a reduction in

00:50:42.020 --> 00:50:45.190
animal products, and hopefully
more people starting to

00:50:45.190 --> 00:50:46.470
eliminate these products.

00:50:46.470 --> 00:50:48.510
So multi-prong approach.

00:50:48.510 --> 00:50:50.920
And within that, we have
legislative initiatives.

00:50:50.920 --> 00:50:53.900
We have corporate outreach
initiatives, looking at

00:50:53.900 --> 00:50:56.640
different power-holders and
stakeholders in this, and how

00:50:56.640 --> 00:50:58.550
we can affect change
within that.

00:51:03.210 --> 00:51:04.460
It's a great question.

00:51:06.900 --> 00:51:09.820
A lot of the success that we've
seen, like Proposition

00:51:09.820 --> 00:51:12.910
2, which I mentioned before,
are citizen-driven ballot

00:51:12.910 --> 00:51:13.690
initiatives.

00:51:13.690 --> 00:51:16.600
A lot of the states where
there is a large farming

00:51:16.600 --> 00:51:21.130
community, the legislature is
not voluntarily going to push

00:51:21.130 --> 00:51:23.360
through any sort of restrictive
measure that would

00:51:23.360 --> 00:51:25.390
challenge such a big
industry there.

00:51:25.390 --> 00:51:28.550
So they require ballot
initiatives to come in,

00:51:28.550 --> 00:51:31.490
because again, consumers are
really on the side of change,

00:51:31.490 --> 00:51:33.870
even when big business isn't.

00:51:33.870 --> 00:51:36.700
But the problem is is that only
about half the states in

00:51:36.700 --> 00:51:38.930
this country allow ballot
initiatives.

00:51:38.930 --> 00:51:42.920
And some of the states, like
Iowa, that has the largest egg

00:51:42.920 --> 00:51:44.710
production and the largest
pork production in this

00:51:44.710 --> 00:51:47.860
country, do not have ballot
initiative processes.

00:51:47.860 --> 00:51:51.650
And their legislature is very
much controlled by big ag.

00:51:51.650 --> 00:51:55.750
So the pathway to affect
legislative change there

00:51:55.750 --> 00:51:57.900
becomes very challenging.

00:51:57.900 --> 00:52:00.980
There is a federal
bill right now.

00:52:00.980 --> 00:52:03.290
It's regarding egg-laying
hens.

00:52:03.290 --> 00:52:06.490
It's not a perfect bill by any
means, but it would set the

00:52:06.490 --> 00:52:10.800
first federal standards for
animals on factory farms.

00:52:10.800 --> 00:52:12.870
It would increase the amount
of space that hens have in

00:52:12.870 --> 00:52:14.190
these cages.

00:52:14.190 --> 00:52:17.260
That is really the first federal
bill that has found

00:52:17.260 --> 00:52:23.530
its way to Congress for farm
animals in over 30 years.

00:52:23.530 --> 00:52:27.630
And the pork and the beef
industries are fighting

00:52:27.630 --> 00:52:30.150
desperately against that bill,
because they don't want to see

00:52:30.150 --> 00:52:32.380
any sort of precedent
set on it.

00:52:32.380 --> 00:52:36.440
So it's challenging, as we
know legislation can be.

00:52:36.440 --> 00:52:37.870
There are a number of
states right now--

00:52:37.870 --> 00:52:40.630
I think New Jersey is one of
them-- that are considering a

00:52:40.630 --> 00:52:44.060
gestation crate ban in
their legislature.

00:52:44.060 --> 00:52:47.780
So that's the main one
that comes to mind.

00:52:47.780 --> 00:52:50.480
I don't think, unfortunately,
that Texas has anything

00:52:50.480 --> 00:52:54.520
currently that's pending
for farm animals.

00:52:54.520 --> 00:52:56.040
So that's sort of the
situation with

00:52:56.040 --> 00:52:57.290
legislation right now.

00:53:03.090 --> 00:53:04.820
Yeah, it's a good question.

00:53:04.820 --> 00:53:07.680
We're not against
food production.

00:53:07.680 --> 00:53:09.480
Everyone has to eat.

00:53:09.480 --> 00:53:12.120
And there are such
thing as tofu

00:53:12.120 --> 00:53:14.000
factories that create jobs.

00:53:14.000 --> 00:53:18.800
There are things, soy milk
factories that create jobs,

00:53:18.800 --> 00:53:20.840
carrot factories that
create jobs.

00:53:20.840 --> 00:53:24.030
So this isn't getting rid
of a bunch of jobs.

00:53:24.030 --> 00:53:27.930
It's a shift in the economy,
in where those jobs go.

00:53:27.930 --> 00:53:30.040
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

00:53:30.040 --> 00:53:31.830
NATHAN RUNKLE: Exactly.

00:53:31.830 --> 00:53:33.760
That's exactly right.

00:53:33.760 --> 00:53:38.160
By one industry shrinking or
doing away, a lot of times

00:53:38.160 --> 00:53:41.040
other industries take their
place that are more

00:53:41.040 --> 00:53:42.400
environmentally sound, are more

00:53:42.400 --> 00:53:43.900
progressive, are more ethical.

00:53:43.900 --> 00:53:45.030
So that's really what
we're looking at.

00:53:45.030 --> 00:53:47.420
So we're just looking at a shift
and a humane economy.

00:53:52.160 --> 00:53:56.440
Yeah, I think we do the
best that we can.

00:53:56.440 --> 00:53:59.440
This isn't a competition
or a purity test.

00:53:59.440 --> 00:54:02.490
So we can eliminate
meat, great.

00:54:02.490 --> 00:54:05.530
If we can reduce it on Mondays,
Tuesdays, and/or

00:54:05.530 --> 00:54:10.350
Wednesdays, great, because we
don't want anyone to feel

00:54:10.350 --> 00:54:10.960
overwhelmed.

00:54:10.960 --> 00:54:13.360
We don't want people to feel
like either I'm part of the

00:54:13.360 --> 00:54:16.160
vegan team or I'm part of the
I'm gonna eat factory farm

00:54:16.160 --> 00:54:18.890
products every meal and not
care about the issue team,

00:54:18.890 --> 00:54:21.420
because that doesn't solve
anything either.

00:54:21.420 --> 00:54:24.140
So I think that's really
the take-home message--

00:54:24.140 --> 00:54:25.390
do the best that you can.

